ral_normalized": false, "mention": "dopaminergic neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8142243027687073, "span": {"begin": 870, "end": 890}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dopaminergic neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8503079414367676, "span": {"begin": 964, "end": 984}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "reactive glial cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.758653461933136, "span": {"begin": 1133, "end": 1153}}, {"id": ["CL:0000129"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "microglia", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.819939136505127, "span": {"begin": 1155, "end": 1164}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "astrocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7846336960792542, "span": {"begin": 1169, "end": 1179}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6733988523483276, "span": {"begin": 1190, "end": 1197}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4843"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "i-NOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9593518376350403, "span": {"begin": 1346, "end": 1351}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.638711154460907, "span": {"begin": 1378, "end": 1385}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glial cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8489787578582764, "span": {"begin": 1454, "end": 1465}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DA neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7403661012649536, "span": {"begin": 1533, "end": 1543}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Circulating monocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7990869283676147, "span": {"begin": 1607, "end": 1628}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lymphocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7556098103523254, "span": {"begin": 1633, "end": 1644}}, {"id": ["mesh:D020078"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Neuroinflammation", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9998317956924438, "span": {"begin": 1646, "end": 1663}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "circulating monocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7733379006385803, "span": {"begin": 1756, "end": 1777}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lymphocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6379992365837097, "span": {"begin": 1782, "end": 1793}}, {"id": ["CL:0000084"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6203895807266235, "span": {"begin": 1838, "end": 1844}}, {"id": ["mim:168600"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PD", "obj": "disease", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1890, "end": 1892}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9858812093734741, "span": {"begin": 1893, "end": 1901}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lymphocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7766727805137634, "span": {"begin": 2012, "end": 2023}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "striatal DA terminals", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4994067847728729, "span": {"begin": 2050, "end": 2071}}], "text": "Histopathological studies have shown that glial activation is a hallmark of every neurodegenerative disease, including Parkinson&rsquo;s disease (Whitton, 2007&nbsp;; Tansey and Goldberg, 2009&nbsp;; Niranjan, 2014&nbsp;; Verkhratiky et al., 2014). PET studies in PD patients have revealed that microglial activation in the substantia nigra is an early event in the disease process (Iannaccone et al., 2012), and that it is extremely persistent. The role of astrocytes is less clear than the one of microglia, but reactive astrocytes are able to release neurotoxic molecules (Mena and Garcia de Ybenes, 2008&nbsp;; Niranjan, 2014). However, astrocytes may also be protective due to their capacity to quench free radicals and secrete neurotrophic factors. The activation of astrocytes reduces neurotrophic support to neurons, and the proportion of astrocytes surrounding dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra is the lowest for any brain area suggesting that dopaminergic neurons are more vulnerable in terms of glial support (for review, Mena and Garcia de Ybenes, 2008). In vitro co-culture experiments have demonstrated that reactive glial cells (microglia and astrocytes) can kill neurons (Chao et al., 1995&nbsp;; Brown and Bal-Price, 2003&nbsp;; Kraft and Harry, 2011&nbsp;; Taetzsch and Block, 2013), and that interventions with e.g. i-NOS inhibition can rescue the neurons (Yadav et al., 2012; Brzozowski et al., 2015). Direct activation of glial cells with the inflammogen LPS has also resulted in vivo in the death of DA neurons (Sharma and Nehru, 2015; Zhou et al., 2012; Li et al., 2009).  Circulating monocytes and lymphocytes: Neuroinflammation can disrupt blood-brain barrier integrity (Zhao et al., 2007), facilitating infiltration of circulating monocytes and lymphocytes (Machado et al., 2011; Quian et al., 2010). T cell infiltration has been found in CNS tissue of PD patients (Miklossy et al., 2006&nbsp;; Qian et al., 2010), and in animal models, in which depletion or inactivation of lymphocytes has been found to protect striatal DA terminals (for review, Appel et al., 2010).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:21:13 +0000 2026"}